# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: video-container-formats
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] A **container format** (informally, sometimes called a **wrapper**) or **metafile** is a file format that allows multiple data streams to be embedded into a single file, usually along with metadata for identifying and further detailing those streams.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Notable examples of container formats include archive files (such as the ZIP format) and formats used for multimedia playback (such as Matroska, MP4, and AVI).
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Among the earliest cross-platform container formats were Distinguished Encoding Rules and the 1985 Interchange File Format.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Although containers may identify how data or metadata is encoded, they do not actually provide instructions about how to decode that data.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] A program that can open a container must also use an appropriate codec to decode its contents.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] If the program doesn't have the required algorithm, it can't use the contained data.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] In these cases, programs usually emit an error message that complains of a missing codec, which users may be able to acquire.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Container formats can be made to wrap any kind of data.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Though there are some examples of such file formats (e.g.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Microsoft Windows's DLL files), most container formats are specialized for specific data requirements.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] For example, since audio and video streams can be coded and decoded with many different algorithms, a container format may be used to provide the appearance of a single file format to users of multimedia playback software.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] This is the difference in file-size between two files with the same content in a different container.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Support for advanced codec functionality.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Older formats such as AVI do not support new codec features like B-frames, VBR audio or VFR video natively.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] The format may be "hacked" to add support, but this creates compatibility problems.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Support for advanced content, such as chapters, subtitles, meta-tags, user-data.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] In addition to pure container formats, which specify *only* the wrapper but not the coding, a number of file formats specify *both* a storage layer and the coding, as part of modular design and forward compatibility.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Examples include the JPEG File Interchange Format (JFIF), for containing JPEG data, and Portable Network Graphics (PNG) formats.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] The container file is used to identify and interleave different data types.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] In most cases, the file header, most of the metadata and the synchro chunks are specified by the container format.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] For example, container formats exist for optimized, low-quality, internet video streaming which differs from high-quality Blu-ray streaming requirements.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Container format parts have various names: "chunks" as in RIFF and PNG, "atoms" in QuickTime/MP4, "packets" in MPEG-TS (from the communications term), and "segments" in JPEG.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] The main content of a chunk is called the "data" or "payload".
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Most container formats have chunks in sequence, each with a header, while TIFF instead stores offsets.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Modular chunks make it easy to recover other chunks in case of file corruption or dropped frames or bit slip, while offsets result in framing errors in cases of bit slip.
[src:video-container-formats/digital-container-format] Other flexible containers can hold many types of audio and video, as well as other media.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] Matroska file extensions are *.mkv* for video (which may include audio, subtitles and chapters), *.mk3d* for stereoscopic video, *.mka* for audio-only files (which may include subtitles), and *.mks* for subtitles only.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] The project was announced on 6 December 2002 as a fork of the Multimedia Container Format (MCF), after disagreements between MCF lead developer Lasse Kärkkäinen and soon-to-be Matroska founder Steve Lhomme about the use of the Extensible Binary Meta Language (EBML) instead of a binary format.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] This coincided with a 6-month coding break by the MCF's lead developer for his military service, during which most of the community quickly migrated to the new project.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] In 2010, it was announced that the WebM audio/video format would be based on a profile of the Matroska container format together with VP8 video and Vorbis audio.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] On 31 October 2014, Microsoft confirmed that Windows 10 would support HEVC and Matroska out of the box, according to a statement from Gabriel Aul, the leader of Microsoft Operating Systems Group's Data and Fundamentals Team.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] Windows 10 Technical Preview Build 9860 added platform level support for HEVC and Matroska.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] In October 2024, Matroska was formally specified in and published as RFC 9559.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] "Matroska" is derived from *matryoshka* (Russian: матрёшка [mɐˈtrʲɵʂkə]), the Russian name for the hollow wooden dolls, better known in English as Russian nesting dolls, which open to expose another smaller doll, that in turn opens to expose another doll, and so on.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] The logo writes it as "Matroška"; the letter š, an "s" with a caron over it, represents the "sh" sound (/ʂ/) in various languages.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] The use of EBML allows extension for future format changes.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] The Matroska team has expressed some of their long-term goals on Doom9.org and Hydrogenaudio forums.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] Matroska is supported by a non-profit organization registered in France.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] It is a royalty-free open standard that is free to use, with the specification being freely available for both private and commercial use.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] The Matroska development team licenses its libraries under the LGPL, with parsing and playback libraries available under BSD licenses.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] Software supporting Matroska include all ffmpeg-based ones, including, notably, mplayer, mpv, VLC, Foobar2000, Media Player Classic-HC, Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Blender, Kdenlive, HandBrake, MKVToolNix as well as YouTube (which uses WebM extensively), and OBS Studio.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] Outside of ffmpeg, Windows 10 supports Matroska natively as well.
[src:video-container-formats/matroska] Earlier versions relied on codec packs (like K-Lite Codec Pack or Combined Community Codec Pack) to integrate ffmpeg (via ffdshow) and other additions into Windows' native DirectShow.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] MPEG-4 Part 14 is a standard specified as a part of the MPEG-4 specifications, formally as **ISO/IEC 14496-14:2003**.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] Unlike the audio-only compression formats MP3 and MP2, MP4 is a container format that can hold various types of media from various codecs.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] During the 2000s, portable media players were sometimes erroneously advertised as "MP4 players", even if they may play a different format like AMV video and not necessarily the MPEG-4 Part 14 format.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] Most kinds of data can be embedded in MPEG-4 Part 14 files through *private streams*.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] A separate hint track is used to include streaming information in the file.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] The registered codecs for MPEG-4 Part 12-based files are published on the website of MP4 Registration authority (mp4ra.org), but most of them are not widely supported by MP4 players.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] The **moov atom** contains information about video resolution, frame rates, orientation, display characteristics, and more.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] It might be placed at the beginning or end of the file.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] In the latter case, the video file is not playable if the file is incomplete (truncated).
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] MP4 files can contain metadata as defined by the format standard, and in addition, can contain Extensible Metadata Platform (XMP) metadata.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] MPEG-4 Part 14 is an instance of the more general ISO/IEC 14496-12:2004 (MPEG-4 Part 12: ISO base media file format), which is directly based upon the QuickTime File Format, which was published in 2001.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] MPEG-4 Part 14 is essentially identical to the QuickTime File Format but formally specifies support for Initial Object Descriptors (IOD) and other MPEG features.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] MPEG-4 Part 14 revises and completely replaces Clause 13 of ISO/IEC 14496-1 (MPEG-4 Part 1: Systems), in which the file format for MPEG-4 content was previously specified.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] The MPEG-4 file format, version 1, was published in 2001 as ISO/IEC 14496-1:2001, which is a revision of the MPEG-4 Part 1: Systems specification published in 1999 (ISO/IEC 14496-1:1999).
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] In 2003, the first version of the MP4 file format was revised and replaced by MPEG-4 Part 14: MP4 file format (ISO/IEC 14496-14:2003), commonly named as MPEG-4 file format version 2.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] The MP4 file format was generalized into the ISO Base Media File format ISO/IEC 14496-12:2004, which defines a general structure for time-based media files.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] It in turn is used as the basis for other file formats in the family (for example, MP4, 3GP, and Motion JPEG 2000).
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] The MP4 file format defined some extensions over the ISO Base Media File Format to support MPEG-4 visual/audio codecs and various MPEG-4 Systems features such as object descriptors and scene descriptions.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] Some of these extensions are also used by other formats based on the ISO base media file format (e.g., 3GP).
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] A list of all registered extensions for ISO Base Media File Format is published on the official registration authority website.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] The registration authority for code-points (identifier values) in "MP4 Family" files is Apple Inc., and it is named in Annex D (informative) in MPEG-4 Part 12.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] Codec designers should register the codes they invent, but registration is not mandatory, and some invented and used code-points are not registered.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] When someone is creating a new specification derived from the ISO Base Media File Format, all the existing specifications should be used both as examples and as a source of definitions and technology.
[src:video-container-formats/mp4-file-format] If an existing specification already covers how a particular media type is stored in the file format (e.g., MPEG-4 audio or video in MP4), that definition should be used, and a new one should not be invented.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The Ogg container format can multiplex a number of independent streams for audio, video, text (such as subtitles), and metadata.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In the Ogg multimedia framework, Theora provides a lossy video layer.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The audio layer is most commonly provided by the music-oriented Vorbis format or its successor Opus.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Lossless audio compression formats include FLAC, and OggPCM.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Until 2007, the `.ogg` filename extension was used for all files whose content used the Ogg container format.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Since then, the Xiph.Org Foundation recommends that `.ogg` only be used for Ogg Vorbis audio files.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Xiph.Org decided to create a new set of file extensions and media types to describe different types of content such as `.oga` for audio only files, `.ogv` for video with or without sound (including Theora), and `.ogx` for multiplexed Ogg.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Ogg's various codecs have been incorporated into a number of different free and proprietary media players, both commercial and non-commercial, as well as portable media players and GPS receivers from different manufacturers.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] As of November 7, 2017, the current version of the Xiph.Org Foundation's reference implementation is libogg 1.3.3.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Another version, libogg2, has been in development, but is awaiting a rewrite as of 2018.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Both software libraries are free software, released under the New BSD License.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Ogg reference implementation was separated from Vorbis on September 2, 2000.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] It was originally named "Squish" but that name was already trademarked, so the project underwent a name change.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The new name, "OggSquish", was used until 2001 when it was changed again to "Ogg".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Ogg has since come to refer to the container format, which is now part of the larger Xiph.org multimedia project.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Today, "Squish" (now known as "Vorbis") refers to a particular audio coding format typically used with the Ogg container format.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Ogg is derived from "ogging", jargon from the computer game *Netrek*, which came to mean doing something forcefully, possibly without consideration of the drain on future resources.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] At its inception, the Ogg project was thought by the authors to be somewhat ambitious given the limited power of the PC hardware of the time.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Although the name Ogg is unrelated to the character Nanny Ogg in Terry Pratchett's Discworld novels, "Vorbis" is named after another Terry Pratchett character from the book *Small Gods*.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The format consists of chunks of data each called an "Ogg page".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Each page begins with the characters "OggS" to identify the file as Ogg format.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] A "serial number" and "page number" in the page header identifies each page as part of a series of pages making up a bitstream.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Multiple bitstreams may be multiplexed in the file where pages from each bitstream are ordered by the seek time of the contained data.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Bitstreams may also be appended to existing files, a process known as "chaining", to cause the bitstreams to be decoded in sequence.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] A BSD-licensed library, called "libvorbis", is available to encode and decode data from "Vorbis" streams.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Independent Ogg implementations are used in several projects such as RealPlayer and a set of DirectShow filters.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Mogg, the "Multi-Track-Single-Logical-Stream Ogg-Vorbis", is the multi-channel or multi-track Ogg file format.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] used to ensure synchronization when parsing Ogg files.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Every page starts with the four ASCII character sequence, "OggS".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This assists in resynchronizing a parser in cases where data has been lost or is corrupted, and is a sanity check before commencing parsing of the page structure.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This field indicates the version of the Ogg bitstream format, to allow for future expansion.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This is an 8 bit field of flags, which indicates the type of page that follows.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] A granule position is the time marker in Ogg files.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] It is an abstract value, whose meaning is determined by the codec.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] It may, for example, be a count of the number of samples, the number of frames or a more complex scheme.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This field is a serial number that identifies a page as belonging to a particular logical bitstream.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Each logical bitstream in a file has a unique value, and this field allows implementations to deliver the pages to the appropriate decoder.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This field is a monotonically increasing field for each logical bitstream.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This allows implementations to detect when data has been lost.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] checksum of the data in the entire page (including the page header, calculated with the checksum field set to 0).
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This allows verification that the data has not been corrupted since it was authored.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Pages that fail the checksum should be discarded.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The checksum is generated using a polynomial value of 0x04C11DB7.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This field indicates the number of segments that exist in this page.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] It also indicates how many bytes are in the segment table that follows this field.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] There can be a maximum of 255 segments in any one page.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The segment table is an array of 8-bit values, each indicating the length of the corresponding segment within the page body.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The number of segments is determined from the preceding page segments field.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Each segment is between 0 and 255 bytes in length.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The segments provide a way to group segments into packets, which are meaningful units of data for the decoder.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] When the segment's length is indicated to be 255, this indicates that the following segment is to be concatenated to this one and is part of the same packet.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] When the segment's length is 0–254, this indicates that this segment is the final segment in this packet.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Where a packet's length is a multiple of 255, the final segment is length 0.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Where the final packet continues on the next page, the final segment value is 255, and the continuation flag is set on the following page to indicate that the start of the new page is a continuation of last page.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] VorbisComment is a base-level Metadata format initially authored for use with Ogg Vorbis.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] It has since been adopted in the specifications of Ogg encapsulations for other Xiph.Org codecs including Theora, Speex, FLAC and Opus.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] *VorbisComment* is the simplest and most widely supported mechanism for storing metadata with Xiph.Org codecs.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Notably, one or more METADATA_BLOCK_PICTURE=... in a *VorbisComment* for thumbnails and cover art have Base64-encoded values of the corresponding FLAC METADATA_BLOCK_PICTURE.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In other words, FLAC stores thumbnails and cover art in binary blocks—outside of the FLAC tags in a little-endian METADATA_BLOCK_VORBIS_COMMENT.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The Ogg project began with a simple audio compression package as part of a larger project in 1993.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The software was originally named *Squish* but due to an existing trade mark it was renamed to *OggSquish*.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This name was later used for the whole Ogg project.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In 1997, the Xiphophorus OggSquish was described as "an attempt both to create a flexible compressed audio format for modern audio applications as well as to provide the first audio format that is common on any and every modern computer platform".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The OggSquish was in 2000 referred to as "a group of several related multimedia and signal processing projects".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In 2000, two projects were in active development for planned release: Ogg Vorbis format and libvorbis—the reference implementation of Vorbis.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Research also included work on future video and lossless audio coding.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In 2001, OggSquish was renamed to *Ogg* and it was described as "the umbrella for a group of several related multimedia and signal processing projects".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Ogg has come to stand for the file format, as part of the larger Xiph.org multimedia project.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Squish became just the name of one of the Ogg codecs.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In 2009, Ogg is described as "a multimedia container format, and the native file and stream format for the Xiph.org multimedia codecs".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The Ogg reference implementation was separated from Vorbis on September 2, 2000.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In May 2003, two Internet RFCs were published relating to the format.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The Ogg bitstream was defined in RFC 3533 (which is classified as 'informative') and its Internet content type (`application/ogg`) in RFC 3534 (which is, as of 2006, a proposed standard protocol).
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In September 2008, RFC 3534 was obsoleted by RFC 5334, which added content types `video/ogg`, `audio/ogg` and filename extensions .ogx, .ogv, .oga, .spx.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] In 2002, the lack of formal video support in Ogg resulted in the development of the *OGM* file format, a hack on Ogg that allowed embedding of video from the Microsoft DirectShow framework into an Ogg-based wrapper.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] OGM was initially supported only by closed source Windows-only tools, but the codebase was subsequently opened.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Later, video (and subtitle) support were formally specified for Ogg but in a manner incompatible with OGM.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Independently, the Matroska container format reached maturity and provided an alternative for people interested in combining Vorbis audio and arbitrary video codecs.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] As a result, OGM is no longer supported or developed and is formally discouraged by Xiph.org.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Today, video in Ogg is found with the .ogv file extension, which is formally specified and officially supported.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Software and codecs that support .ogm files are available without charge.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The more popular Vorbis codec had built-in support on many software players, and extensions were available for nearly all the rest.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] On May 16, 2007, the Free Software Foundation started a campaign to increase the use of Vorbis "as an ethically, legally and technically superior audio alternative to the proprietary MP3 format".
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] People were also encouraged to support the campaign by adding a web button to their website or blog.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] By June 30, 2009, the Ogg container, through the use of the Theora and Vorbis, was the only container format included in Firefox 3.5 web browser's implementation of the HTML5 `<video>` and `<audio>` elements.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] This was in accordance with the original recommendation outlined in, but later removed from, the HTML5 draft specification (see Ogg controversy).
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] On March 3, 2010, a technical analysis by an FFmpeg developer was critical about the general purpose abilities of Ogg as a multimedia container format.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The author of Ogg later responded to these claims in an article of his own.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The actual audio or video encoded by a codec is stored inside an Ogg container.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Ogg containers may contain streams encoded with multiple codecs; for example, a video file with sound contains data encoded by both an audio codec and a video codec.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Ogg audio media is registered as IANA media type audio/ogg with file extensions .oga, .ogg, and .spx.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] It is a proper subset of the Ogg video media type video/ogg with file extension .ogv.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] Other Ogg applications use media type application/ogg with file extension .ogx; this is a superset of video/ogg.
[src:video-container-formats/ogg] The Opus media type audio/opus with file extension .opus was registered later in RFC 7587 and 7845.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] The format specifies a multimedia container file that contains one or more tracks, each of which stores a particular type of data: audio, video, or text (e.g. for subtitles).
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] Each track either contains a digitally-encoded media stream (using a specific format) or a data reference to the media stream located in another file.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] Tracks are maintained in a hierarchical data structure consisting of objects called atoms.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] An atom can be a parent to other atoms or it can contain media or edit data, but it is not supposed to do both.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] The ability to contain abstract data references for the media data, and the separation of the media data from the media offsets and the track edit lists means that QuickTime is particularly suited for editing, as it is capable of importing and editing in place (without data copying).
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] Other later-developed media container formats such as Microsoft's Advanced Systems Format or the Matroska and Ogg containers lack this abstraction, and require all media data to be rewritten after editing.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] Because both the QuickTime and MP4 container formats can use the same MPEG-4 formats, they are mostly interchangeable in a QuickTime-only environment.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] MP4, being an international standard, has more support.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] This is especially true on hardware devices, such as the PlayStation Portable and various DVD players; on the software side, most DirectShow and Video for Windows codec packs include an MP4 parser, but not one for QTFF.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] In QuickTime Pro's MPEG-4 Export dialog, an option called "Passthrough" allows a clean export to MP4 without affecting the audio or video streams.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] One discrepancy ushered in by QuickTime 7 released on April 29, 2005, is that the QuickTime file format supports multichannel audio (used, for example, in the high-definition trailers on Apple's site).
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] The International Organization for Standardization approved the QuickTime file format as the basis of the MPEG-4 file format.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] The MPEG-4 file format specification was created on the basis of the QuickTime format specification published in 2001.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] The MP4 (.mp4) file format was published in 2001 as the revision of the MPEG-4 Part 1: Systems specification published in 1999 (ISO/IEC 14496-1:2001).
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] In 2003, the first version of MP4 format was revised and replaced by MPEG-4 Part 14: MP4 file format (ISO/IEC 14496-14:2003).
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] It in turn is used as the basis for other multimedia file formats (for example 3GP, Motion JPEG 2000).
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] A list of all registered extensions for ISO Base Media File Format is published on the official registration authority website www.mp4ra.org.
[src:video-container-formats/quicktime-file-format] This registration authority for code-points in "MP4 Family" files is Apple Inc. and it is named in Annex D (informative) in MPEG-4 Part 12.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The WebM container is based on a profile of Matroska.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] WebM initially supported VP8 video and Vorbis audio streams.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In 2013, it was updated to accommodate VP9 video and Opus audio.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Native WebM support by Mozilla Firefox, Opera, and Google Chrome was announced at the 2010 Google I/O conference.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Internet Explorer 9 requires third-party WebM software.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In 2021, Apple released Safari 14.1 for macOS, which added native WebM support to the browser.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] As of 2019, QuickTime does not natively support WebM, but does with a suitable third-party plug-in.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In 2011, the Google WebM Project Team released plugins for Internet Explorer and Safari to allow playback of WebM files through the standard HTML5 `<video>` tag.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] As of 9 June 2012, Internet Explorer 9 and later supported the plugin for Windows Vista and later.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] VLC media player, MPlayer, K-Multimedia Player and JRiver Media Center have native support for playing WebM files.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] FFmpeg can encode and decode VP8 videos when built with support for libvpx, the VP8/VP9 codec library of the WebM project, as well as mux/demux WebM-compliant files.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] On July 23, 2010 Fiona Glaser, Ronald Bultje, and David Conrad of the FFmpeg team announced the ffvp8 decoder.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Their testing found that ffvp8 was faster than Google's own libvpx decoder.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] MKVToolNix, the popular Matroska creation tools, implemented support for multiplexing/demultiplexing WebM-compliant files out of the box.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Haali Media Splitter also announced support for muxing/demuxing of WebM.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Since version 1.4.9, the LiVES video editor has support for realtime decoding and for encoding to WebM format using ffmpeg libraries.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] MPC-HC since build SVN 2071 supports WebM playback with internal VP8 decoder based on FFmpeg's code.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The full decoding support for WebM is available in MPC-HC since version 1.4.2499.0.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Android is WebM-enabled since version 2.3 Gingerbread, which was first made available via the Nexus S smartphone and streamable since Android 4.0 Ice Cream Sandwich.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The Microsoft Edge browser supports WebM since April 2016.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] On July 30, 2019, Blender 2.80 was released with WebM support.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] iOS did not natively play WebM until 2021, when support for WebM was added in Safari 15 as part of iOS 15.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The Sony PlayStation 5 supports capturing 1080p and 2160p footage in WebM format.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] ChromeOS screen recordings are saved as WebM files.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] WebM Project licenses VP8 hardware accelerators (RTL IP) to semiconductor companies for 1080p encoding and decoding at zero cost.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] AMD, ARM and Broadcom have announced support for hardware acceleration of the WebM format.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Intel is also considering hardware-based acceleration for WebM in its Atom-based TV chips if the format gains popularity.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Qualcomm and Texas Instruments have announced support, with native support coming to the TI OMAP processor.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Chips&Media have announced a fully hardware decoder for VP8 that can decode full HD resolution (1080p) VP8 streams at 60 frames per second.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Nvidia is supporting VP8 and provides both hardware decoding and encoding in the Tegra 4 and Tegra 4i SoCs.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Nvidia announced 3D video support for WebM through HTML5 and their Nvidia 3D Vision technology.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] On January 7, 2011, Rockchip released the world's first chip to host a full hardware implementation of 1080p VP8 decoding.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The video acceleration in the RK29xx chip is handled by the WebM Project's G-Series 1 hardware decoder IP.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In June 2011, ZiiLABS demonstrated their 1080p VP8 decoder implementation running on the ZMS-20 processor.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The chip's programmable media processing array is used to provide the VP8 acceleration.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] ST-Ericsson and Huawei also had hardware implementations in their computer chips.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Since 2017, Icecast — a streaming media server traditionally used for audio streaming — has supported live video streaming using the WebM format (VP8/VP9/AV1 video codecs with Vorbis/Opus audio codecs).
[src:video-container-formats/webm] This enables broadcasting of high-quality, royalty-free, open-standard video streams that can be played directly in browsers without requiring proprietary plugins or players.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Archived streams and server listings demonstrate WebM's viability for live streaming over Icecast, including examples of 1080p VP9 streams.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Current implementations include live streams accessible at https://rdst.win:59000/dos.webm, with server status visible at https://rdst.win:59000.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The original WebM license terminated both patent grants and copyright redistribution terms if a patent infringement lawsuit was filed, causing concerns around GPL compatibility.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In response to those concerns, the WebM Project decoupled the patent grant from the copyright grant, offering the code under a standard BSD license and patents under a separate grant.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] The Free Software Foundation, which maintains The Free Software Definition, has given its endorsement for WebM and VP8 and considers the software's license to be compatible with the GNU General Public License.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] On January 19, 2011, the Free Software Foundation announced its official support for the WebM project.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In February 2011, Microsoft's Vice President of Internet Explorer called upon Google to provide indemnification against patent suits.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Although Google has irrevocably released all of its patents on VP8 as a royalty-free format, the MPEG LA, licensors of the H.264 patent pool, have expressed interest in creating a patent pool for VP8.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Conversely, other researchers cite evidence that On2 made a particular effort to avoid any MPEG LA patents.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] As a result of the threat, the United States Department of Justice (DOJ) started an investigation in March 2011 into the MPEG LA for its role in possibly attempting to stifle competition.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In March 2013, MPEG LA announced that it had reached an agreement with Google to license patents that "may be essential" for the implementation of the VP8 codec, and give Google the right to sub-license these patents to any third-party user of VP8 or VP9.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] In March 2013, Nokia filed an objection to the Internet Engineering Task Force concerning Google's proposal for the VP8 codec to be a core part of WebM, saying it holds essential patents to VP8's implementation.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] Nokia listed 64 patents and 22 pending applications, adding it was not prepared to license any of them for VP8.
[src:video-container-formats/webm] On August 5, 2013, a court in Mannheim, Germany, ruled that VP8 does not infringe a patent owned and asserted by Nokia.
